        <td bgColor="black"><textarea cols="70" name="Message" rows="12" wrap="VIRTUAL">[quote]
Blah...

That's the over all feeling I get when I begin to think about the MMOG genre, and the games that are coming out for it.

I can't help but look at the whole scene and realize that, honestly, it's not improving, and it's not moving forward.

Between myself and a fellow hard-core gamer I've had access to, or a plethora of information from, a fair number of betas and "just around the corner" games. One by one they've dropped like flies on our to-get list. This includes not only Fantasy, but space MMOGs as well.

(No. SW:G is not included in this list, I have no information from that title).

My personal goal was to find a game and/or company better than EQ/Varant. Something I myself and my close friends could go to and get away from the stagnation and endless BS experienced in the game and handed down from the company.

In my own heavily biased opinion, Varant is a horrible company with a track record that should have them in ruin, not having folks continuing to buy their products. I can not, currently, think of another company who seems to be (at least at times) so blatantly ignorant of their own product, or who repeatedly makes changes with a total lack of regard to quality, or the opinion/feelings of their customer base.

So it's very disapointing that, even with such an opinion, I still can not find a product or game company that is worth moving to. It makes no sense to me to move to a seperate company for the simple sake of not using a Varant product; it has to be a better product in the first place or the move would be pointless.

When it comes right down to it, EQ is the best.  Both of what's currently available and from what's about to hit (in my opinion, at least). It should be obvious that I don't say this out of any admiration for the company. Rather, I've always been the sort who's tried to eat crow when I need to, to be honest about things, and accept truths even when I don't agree with them. In my opinion, this is just the way that it is, whether I like it or not.

There does not seem to be any company out there who can successfully execute a good idea. MMOGs are going to raise to the surface, as they have been, and then fall right back under after a fair bit of starting noise... as they have been.

EQ2 is going to be a severe level camp from the sounds of it, but folks will go to that because none of the competition seems adequate. They'll look at 'em, they'll try them, but just as with DAoC most are going to turn back to the EQ worlds due to lack of interest / content / etc.

The only two MMOGs I see that could pose a formidable challenge are WoW, and Final Fantasy Online.

I suppose, ultimately, I'm disenchanted with the whole genre. This is my own fault for having such high hopes for it.  When it comes down to it, what I think we're addicted to is not EQ but rather the genre itself, and EQ just happens to be the best choice for it at this moment.  The thought of playing a single player game now ranks somewhere along with playing an old Atari game.

I'm really too tired to continue this. I have no clue where the time's gone but I seem to have lots the entire night.. o.0 hmph, anyways, there's not too much to say on the subject other than I think the whole genre is sinking. If not in a financial sense, then certainly in quality.

I suppose all that there's left to say, is: Kupo.

~Mysk
Who's ponderously curious where the last, oh, three hours have gone. :-&

